TopicTitle: [1.12.x] Cryogenic Engines: Liquid Hydrogen and Methane Rockets! (Jan 22, 2022)

Articles.Content: Logging does tend to create a fair bit of gc alloc.  If it's happening every frame it might be worth worrying about.

It's... not though. If someone can demonstrably prove that it is, fine, there's something not right.

Really - 1-3 log messages will be sent per vessel when:

- A vessel goes on rails
- A vessel is destroyed
- A vessel's part count changes
- A vessel is loaded into the scene

If there are a lot of vessels in the game this might give the appearance of constant logging.

That sounds very reasonable to me.

The "right" way to do it is probably with a debug switch. However, I've noticed in the past that with boiloff issues, the ones that I haven't found are terrible edge cases - so I thought I would help the player by making their logs provide me with most of the information automatically. At least at the start.

Sorry the brevity of the post I think you refer to made it difficult for me to realize that the output is deliberate at this stage of development. I am trying to wade through masses of output atm, trying to find any mods that are not quite perfected for 1.3 yet.

[@Nertea](https://forum.kerbalspaceprogram.com/index.php?/profile/83952-nertea/) where does the dependency on Dynamic Battery Storage come in?

> 
>

> 
> 
> This mod will start showing up on <abbr title="Comprehensive Kerbal Archive Network (a KSP mod manager)">CKAN</abbr> now, but there may be an issue with the metadata.  Please avoid installing with <abbr title="Comprehensive Kerbal Archive Network (a KSP mod manager)">CKAN</abbr> for the moment.

> 
> [@Nertea](https://forum.kerbalspaceprogram.com/index.php?/profile/83952-nertea/) where does the dependency on Dynamic Battery Storage come in?
> 

DBS is for managing any kind of large passive electricity draws. Without it some of the larger cryo tanks (say anything above ~40-50 Ec/x draw) will start malfunctioning at high timewarp due to the stock resource handling. So it's a shared dependency in any of my mods that deal with passive Ec consumption like NFElectrical, CryoTanks (CE/KA) and FFT.

To me, it looks about right, because if you look at your <abbr title="Thrust-to-weight ratio">TWR</abbr>, you can stack a serious amount of extra fuel onto the emancipator and you may see the increase in <abbr title="Delta-V">dV</abbr>. You aren't supposed to use the same amount of fuel on this one. The <abbr title="Specific Impulse (rocketry) or Internet Service Provider">ISP</abbr> is 2850 with 12400 kN of thrust compared to the <abbr title="Liquid Fuel">LF</abbr>/O engine with 345 <abbr title="Specific Impulse (rocketry) or Internet Service Provider">ISP</abbr> and 480 kN of thrust.

[@Kerbrian](https://forum.kerbalspaceprogram.com/index.php?/profile/170801-kerbrian/) If you don't mind a bit of math this can be easily understood through the rocket equation, [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tsiolkovsky_rocket_equation](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tsiolkovsky_rocket_equation)

Just punch in your values to deltaV = <abbr title="Specific Impulse (rocketry) or Internet Service Provider">ISP</abbr> \* 9.81 \* ln( M0 / Mf ). You will see while a high <abbr title="Specific Impulse (rocketry) or Internet Service Provider">ISP</abbr> engine is heavy as you add more fuel (increasing the ratio of wet mass to dry mass) you will achieve much better performance. For large/equal ratios of M0:Mf the <abbr title="Specific Impulse (rocketry) or Internet Service Provider">ISP</abbr> becomes dominate in determining deltaV.
